1
0:00:15.26,000 --> 0:00:17,000
Each of you possesses

2
0:00:17.26,000 --> 0:00:2,000
the most powerful, dangerous and subversive trait

3
0:00:20.26,000 --> 0:00:23,000
that natural selection has ever devised.

4
0:00:23.26,000 --> 0:00:26,000
It's a piece of neural audio technology

5
0:00:26.26,000 --> 0:00:28,000
for rewiring other people's minds.

6
0:00:28.26,000 --> 0:00:31,000
I'm talking about your language, of course,

7
0:00:31.26,000 --> 0:00:34,000
because it allows you to implant a thought from your mind

8
0:00:34.26,000 --> 0:00:37,000
directly into someone else's mind,

9
0:00:37.26,000 --> 0:00:39,000
and they can attempt to do the same to you,

10
0:00:39.26,000 --> 0:00:42,000
without either of you having to perform surgery.

11
0:00:42.26,000 --> 0:00:44,000
Instead, when you speak,

12
0:00:44.26,000 --> 0:00:46,000
you're actually using a form of telemetry

13
0:00:46.26,000 --> 0:00:48,000
not so different

14
0:00:48.26,000 --> 0:00:5,000
from the remote control device for your television.

15
0:00:50.26,000 --> 0:00:52,000
It's just that, whereas that device

16
0:00:52.26,000 --> 0:00:54,000
relies on pulses of infrared light,

17
0:00:54.26,000 --> 0:00:57,000
your language relies on pulses,

18
0:00:57.26,000 --> 0:00:59,000
discrete pulses, of sound.

19
0:00:59.26,000 --> 0:01:02,000
And just as you use the remote control device

20
0:01:02.26,000 --> 0:01:04,000
to alter the internal settings of your television

21
0:01:04.26,000 --> 0:01:06,000
to suit your mood,

22
0:01:06.26,000 --> 0:01:08,000
you use your language

23
0:01:08.26,000 --> 0:01:1,000
to alter the settings inside someone else's brain

24
0:01:10.26,000 --> 0:01:12,000
to suit your interests.

25
0:01:12.26,000 --> 0:01:14,000
Languages are genes talking,

26
0:01:14.26,000 --> 0:01:16,000
getting things that they want.

27
0:01:16.26,000 --> 0:01:19,000
And just imagine the sense of wonder in a baby

28
0:01:19.26,000 --> 0:01:22,000
when it first discovers that, merely by uttering a sound,

29
0:01:22.26,000 --> 0:01:24,000
it can get objects to move across a room

30
0:01:24.26,000 --> 0:01:26,000
as if by magic,

31
0:01:26.26,000 --> 0:01:29,000
and maybe even into its mouth.

32
0:01:29.26,000 --> 0:01:31,000
Now language's subversive power

33
0:01:31.26,000 --> 0:01:33,000
has been recognized throughout the ages

34
0:01:33.26,000 --> 0:01:35,000
in censorship, in books you can't read,

35
0:01:35.26,000 --> 0:01:37,000
phrases you can't use

36
0:01:37.26,000 --> 0:01:39,000
and words you can't say.

37
0:01:39.26,000 --> 0:01:42,000
In fact, the Tower of Babel story in the Bible

38
0:01:42.26,000 --> 0:01:44,000
is a fable and warning

39
0:01:44.26,000 --> 0:01:46,000
about the power of language.

40
0:01:46.26,000 --> 0:01:49,000
According to that story, early humans developed the conceit

41
0:01:49.26,000 --> 0:01:51,000
that, by using their language to work together,

42
0:01:51.26,000 --> 0:01:53,000
they could build a tower

43
0:01:53.26,000 --> 0:01:55,000
that would take them all the way to heaven.

44
0:01:55.26,000 --> 0:01:58,000
Now God, angered at this attempt to usurp his power,

45
0:01:58.26,000 --> 0:02:01,000
destroyed the tower,

46
0:02:01.26,000 --> 0:02:03,000
and then to ensure

47
0:02:03.26,000 --> 0:02:05,000
that it would never be rebuilt,

48
0:02:05.26,000 --> 0:02:08,000
he scattered the people by giving them different languages --

49
0:02:08.26,000 --> 0:02:11,000
confused them by giving them different languages.

50
0:02:11.26,000 --> 0:02:13,000
And this leads to the wonderful irony

51
0:02:13.26,000 --> 0:02:16,000
that our languages exist to prevent us from communicating.

52
0:02:16.26,000 --> 0:02:18,000
Even today,

53
0:02:18.26,000 --> 0:02:2,000
we know that there are words we cannot use,

54
0:02:20.26,000 --> 0:02:22,000
phrases we cannot say,

55
0:02:22.26,000 --> 0:02:24,000
because if we do so,

56
0:02:24.26,000 --> 0:02:27,000
we might be accosted, jailed,

57
0:02:27.26,000 --> 0:02:29,000
or even killed.

58
0:02:29.26,000 --> 0:02:31,000
And all of this from a puff of air

59
0:02:31.26,000 --> 0:02:33,000
emanating from our mouths.

60
0:02:33.26,000 --> 0:02:36,000
Now all this fuss about a single one of our traits

61
0:02:36.26,000 --> 0:02:38,000
tells us there's something worth explaining.

62
0:02:38.26,000 --> 0:02:4,000
And that is how and why

63
0:02:40.26,000 --> 0:02:42,000
did this remarkable trait evolve,

64
0:02:42.26,000 --> 0:02:44,000
and why did it evolve

65
0:02:44.26,000 --> 0:02:46,000
only in our species?

66
0:02:46.26,000 --> 0:02:48,000
Now it's a little bit of a surprise

67
0:02:48.26,000 --> 0:02:5,000
that to get an answer to that question,

68
0:02:50.26,000 --> 0:02:52,000
we have to go to tool use

69
0:02:52.26,000 --> 0:02:54,000
in the chimpanzees.

70
0:02:54.26,000 --> 0:02:56,000
Now these chimpanzees are using tools,

71
0:02:56.26,000 --> 0:02:59,000
and we take that as a sign of their intelligence.

72
0:02:59.26,000 --> 0:03:01,000
But if they really were intelligent,

73
0:03:01.26,000 --> 0:03:04,000
why would they use a stick to extract termites from the ground

74
0:03:04.26,000 --> 0:03:06,000
rather than a shovel?

75
0:03:06.26,000 --> 0:03:09,000
And if they really were intelligent,

76
0:03:09.26,000 --> 0:03:11,000
why would they crack open nuts with a rock?

77
0:03:11.26,000 --> 0:03:14,000
Why wouldn't they just go to a shop and buy a bag of nuts

78
0:03:14.26,000 --> 0:03:17,000
that somebody else had already cracked open for them?

79
0:03:17.26,000 --> 0:03:19,000
Why not? I mean, that's what we do.

80
0:03:19.26,000 --> 0:03:21,000
Now the reason the chimpanzees don't do that

81
0:03:21.26,000 --> 0:03:24,000
is that they lack what psychologists and anthropologists call

82
0:03:24.26,000 --> 0:03:26,000
social learning.

83
0:03:26.26,000 --> 0:03:28,000
They seem to lack the ability

84
0:03:28.26,000 --> 0:03:3,000
to learn from others

85
0:03:30.26,000 --> 0:03:32,000
by copying or imitating

86
0:03:32.26,000 --> 0:03:34,000
or simply watching.

87
0:03:34.26,000 --> 0:03:36,000
As a result,

88
0:03:36.26,000 --> 0:03:38,000
they can't improve on others' ideas

89
0:03:38.26,000 --> 0:03:4,000
or learn from others' mistakes --

90
0:03:40.26,000 --> 0:03:42,000
benefit from others' wisdom.

91
0:03:42.26,000 --> 0:03:44,000
And so they just do the same thing

92
0:03:44.26,000 --> 0:03:46,000
over and over and over again.

93
0:03:46.26,000 --> 0:03:5,000
In fact, we could go away for a million years and come back

94
0:03:50.26,000 --> 0:03:53,000
and these chimpanzees would be doing the same thing

95
0:03:53.26,000 --> 0:03:55,000
with the same sticks for the termites

96
0:03:55.26,000 --> 0:03:58,000
and the same rocks to crack open the nuts.

97
0:03:58.26,000 --> 0:04:01,000
Now this may sound arrogant, or even full of hubris.

98
0:04:01.26,000 --> 0:04:03,000
How do we know this?

99
0:04:03.26,000 --> 0:04:06,000
Because this is exactly what our ancestors, the Homo erectus, did.

100
0:04:06.26,000 --> 0:04:08,000
These upright apes

101
0:04:08.26,000 --> 0:04:1,000
evolved on the African savanna

102
0:04:10.26,000 --> 0:04:12,000
about two million years ago,

103
0:04:12.26,000 --> 0:04:14,000
and they made these splendid hand axes

104
0:04:14.26,000 --> 0:04:16,000
that fit wonderfully into your hands.

105
0:04:16.26,000 --> 0:04:18,000
But if we look at the fossil record,

106
0:04:18.26,000 --> 0:04:21,000
we see that they made the same hand axe

107
0:04:21.26,000 --> 0:04:23,000
over and over and over again

108
0:04:23.26,000 --> 0:04:25,000
for one million years.

109
0:04:25.26,000 --> 0:04:27,000
You can follow it through the fossil record.

110
0:04:27.26,000 --> 0:04:29,000
Now if we make some guesses about how long Homo erectus lived,

111
0:04:29.26,000 --> 0:04:31,000
what their generation time was,

112
0:04:31.26,000 --> 0:04:34,000
that's about 40,000 generations

113
0:04:34.26,000 --> 0:04:37,000
of parents to offspring, and other individuals watching,

114
0:04:37.26,000 --> 0:04:39,000
in which that hand axe didn't change.

115
0:04:39.26,000 --> 0:04:41,000
It's not even clear

116
0:04:41.26,000 --> 0:04:43,000
that our very close genetic relatives, the Neanderthals,

117
0:04:43.26,000 --> 0:04:45,000
had social learning.

118
0:04:45.26,000 --> 0:04:48,000
Sure enough, their tools were more complicated

119
0:04:48.26,000 --> 0:04:5,000
than those of Homo erectus,

120
0:04:50.26,000 --> 0:04:52,000
but they too showed very little change

121
0:04:52.26,000 --> 0:04:55,000
over the 300,000 years or so

122
0:04:55.26,000 --> 0:04:57,000
that those species, the Neanderthals,

123
0:04:57.26,000 --> 0:04:59,000
lived in Eurasia.

124
0:04:59.26,000 --> 0:05:01,000
Okay, so what this tells us

125
0:05:01.26,000 --> 0:05:04,000
is that, contrary to the old adage,

126
0:05:04.26,000 --> 0:05:07,000
"monkey see, monkey do,"

127
0:05:07.26,000 --> 0:05:09,000
the surprise really is

128
0:05:09.26,000 --> 0:05:11,000
that all of the other animals

129
0:05:11.26,000 --> 0:05:14,000
really cannot do that -- at least not very much.

130
0:05:14.26,000 --> 0:05:16,000
And even this picture

131
0:05:16.26,000 --> 0:05:19,000
has the suspicious taint of being rigged about it --

132
0:05:19.26,000 --> 0:05:21,000
something from a Barnum & Bailey circus.

133
0:05:21.26,000 --> 0:05:23,000
But by comparison,

134
0:05:23.26,000 --> 0:05:25,000
we can learn.

135
0:05:25.26,000 --> 0:05:28,000
We can learn by watching other people

136
0:05:28.26,000 --> 0:05:3,000
and copying or imitating

137
0:05:30.26,000 --> 0:05:32,000
what they can do.

138
0:05:32.26,000 --> 0:05:35,000
We can then choose, from among a range of options,

139
0:05:35.26,000 --> 0:05:37,000
the best one.

140
0:05:37.26,000 --> 0:05:39,000
We can benefit from others' ideas.

141
0:05:39.26,000 --> 0:05:41,000
We can build on their wisdom.

142
0:05:41.26,000 --> 0:05:44,000
And as a result, our ideas do accumulate,

143
0:05:44.26,000 --> 0:05:48,000
and our technology progresses.

144
0:05:48.26,000 --> 0:05:53,000
And this cumulative cultural adaptation,

145
0:05:53.26,000 --> 0:05:55,000
as anthropologists call

146
0:05:55.26,000 --> 0:05:57,000
this accumulation of ideas,

147
0:05:57.26,000 --> 0:05:59,000
is responsible for everything around you

148
0:05:59.26,000 --> 0:06:01,000
in your bustling and teeming everyday lives.

149
0:06:01.26,000 --> 0:06:03,000
I mean the world has changed out of all proportion

150
0:06:03.26,000 --> 0:06:05,000
to what we would recognize

151
0:06:05.26,000 --> 0:06:08,000
even 1,000 or 2,000 years ago.

152
0:06:08.26,000 --> 0:06:11,000
And all of this because of cumulative cultural adaptation.

153
0:06:11.26,000 --> 0:06:13,000
The chairs you're sitting in, the lights in this auditorium,

154
0:06:13.26,000 --> 0:06:16,000
my microphone, the iPads and iPods that you carry around with you --

155
0:06:16.26,000 --> 0:06:18,000
all are a result

156
0:06:18.26,000 --> 0:06:2,000
of cumulative cultural adaptation.

157
0:06:20.26,000 --> 0:06:24,000
Now to many commentators,

158
0:06:24.26,000 --> 0:06:27,000
cumulative cultural adaptation, or social learning,

159
0:06:27.26,000 --> 0:06:3,000
is job done, end of story.

160
0:06:30.26,000 --> 0:06:33,000
Our species can make stuff,

161
0:06:33.26,000 --> 0:06:36,000
therefore we prospered in a way that no other species has.

162
0:06:36.26,000 --> 0:06:39,000
In fact, we can even make the "stuff of life" --

163
0:06:39.26,000 --> 0:06:41,000
as I just said, all the stuff around us.

164
0:06:41.26,000 --> 0:06:43,000
But in fact, it turns out

165
0:06:43.26,000 --> 0:06:46,000
that some time around 200,000 years ago,

166
0:06:46.26,000 --> 0:06:48,000
when our species first arose

167
0:06:48.26,000 --> 0:06:5,000
and acquired social learning,

168
0:06:50.26,000 --> 0:06:52,000
that this was really the beginning of our story,

169
0:06:52.26,000 --> 0:06:54,000
not the end of our story.

170
0:06:54.26,000 --> 0:06:57,000
Because our acquisition of social learning

171
0:06:57.26,000 --> 0:07:,000
would create a social and evolutionary dilemma,

172
0:07:00.26,000 --> 0:07:03,000
the resolution of which, it's fair to say,

173
0:07:03.26,000 --> 0:07:07,000
would determine not only the future course of our psychology,

174
0:07:07.26,000 --> 0:07:09,000
but the future course of the entire world.

175
0:07:09.26,000 --> 0:07:12,000
And most importantly for this,

176
0:07:12.26,000 --> 0:07:15,000
it'll tell us why we have language.

177
0:07:15.26,000 --> 0:07:17,000
And the reason that dilemma arose

178
0:07:17.26,000 --> 0:07:2,000
is, it turns out, that social learning is visual theft.

179
0:07:20.26,000 --> 0:07:23,000
If I can learn by watching you,

180
0:07:23.26,000 --> 0:07:25,000
I can steal your best ideas,

181
0:07:25.26,000 --> 0:07:28,000
and I can benefit from your efforts,

182
0:07:28.26,000 --> 0:07:3,000
without having to put in the time and energy that you did

183
0:07:30.26,000 --> 0:07:32,000
into developing them.

184
0:07:32.26,000 --> 0:07:35,000
If I can watch which lure you use to catch a fish,

185
0:07:35.26,000 --> 0:07:37,000
or I can watch how you flake your hand axe

186
0:07:37.26,000 --> 0:07:39,000
to make it better,

187
0:07:39.26,000 --> 0:07:42,000
or if I follow you secretly to your mushroom patch,

188
0:07:42.26,000 --> 0:07:45,000
I can benefit from your knowledge and wisdom and skills,

189
0:07:45.26,000 --> 0:07:47,000
and maybe even catch that fish

190
0:07:47.26,000 --> 0:07:49,000
before you do.

191
0:07:49.26,000 --> 0:07:52,000
Social learning really is visual theft.

192
0:07:52.26,000 --> 0:07:54,000
And in any species that acquired it,

193
0:07:54.26,000 --> 0:07:56,000
it would behoove you

194
0:07:56.26,000 --> 0:07:58,000
to hide your best ideas,

195
0:07:58.26,000 --> 0:08:01,000
lest somebody steal them from you.

196
0:08:02.26,000 --> 0:08:05,000
And so some time around 200,000 years ago,

197
0:08:05.26,000 --> 0:08:08,000
our species confronted this crisis.

198
0:08:08.26,000 --> 0:08:11,000
And we really had only two options

199
0:08:11.26,000 --> 0:08:13,000
for dealing with the conflicts

200
0:08:13.26,000 --> 0:08:15,000
that visual theft would bring.

201
0:08:15.26,000 --> 0:08:17,000
One of those options

202
0:08:17.26,000 --> 0:08:2,000
was that we could have retreated

203
0:08:20.26,000 --> 0:08:22,000
into small family groups.

204
0:08:22.26,000 --> 0:08:25,000
Because then the benefits of our ideas and knowledge

205
0:08:25.26,000 --> 0:08:27,000
would flow just to our relatives.

206
0:08:27.26,000 --> 0:08:29,000
Had we chosen this option,

207
0:08:29.26,000 --> 0:08:32,000
sometime around 200,000 years ago,

208
0:08:32.26,000 --> 0:08:35,000
we would probably still be living like the Neanderthals were

209
0:08:35.26,000 --> 0:08:38,000
when we first entered Europe 40,000 years ago.

210
0:08:38.26,000 --> 0:08:4,000
And this is because in small groups

211
0:08:40.26,000 --> 0:08:43,000
there are fewer ideas, there are fewer innovations.

212
0:08:43.26,000 --> 0:08:46,000
And small groups are more prone to accidents and bad luck.

213
0:08:46.26,000 --> 0:08:48,000
So if we'd chosen that path,

214
0:08:48.26,000 --> 0:08:51,000
our evolutionary path would have led into the forest --

215
0:08:51.26,000 --> 0:08:53,000
and been a short one indeed.

216
0:08:53.26,000 --> 0:08:55,000
The other option we could choose

217
0:08:55.26,000 --> 0:08:58,000
was to develop the systems of communication

218
0:08:58.26,000 --> 0:09:,000
that would allow us to share ideas

219
0:09:00.26,000 --> 0:09:03,000
and to cooperate amongst others.

220
0:09:03.26,000 --> 0:09:05,000
Choosing this option would mean

221
0:09:05.26,000 --> 0:09:08,000
that a vastly greater fund of accumulated knowledge and wisdom

222
0:09:08.26,000 --> 0:09:11,000
would become available to any one individual

223
0:09:11.26,000 --> 0:09:14,000
than would ever arise from within an individual family

224
0:09:14.26,000 --> 0:09:17,000
or an individual person on their own.

225
0:09:18.26,000 --> 0:09:21,000
Well, we chose the second option,

226
0:09:21.26,000 --> 0:09:24,000
and language is the result.

227
0:09:24.26,000 --> 0:09:26,000
Language evolved to solve the crisis

228
0:09:26.26,000 --> 0:09:28,000
of visual theft.

229
0:09:28.26,000 --> 0:09:31,000
Language is a piece of social technology

230
0:09:31.26,000 --> 0:09:34,000
for enhancing the benefits of cooperation --

231
0:09:34.26,000 --> 0:09:37,000
for reaching agreements, for striking deals

232
0:09:37.26,000 --> 0:09:41,000
and for coordinating our activities.

233
0:09:41.26,000 --> 0:09:43,000
And you can see that, in a developing society

234
0:09:43.26,000 --> 0:09:45,000
that was beginning to acquire language,

235
0:09:45.26,000 --> 0:09:47,000
not having language

236
0:09:47.26,000 --> 0:09:49,000
would be a like a bird without wings.

237
0:09:49.26,000 --> 0:09:52,000
Just as wings open up this sphere of air

238
0:09:52.26,000 --> 0:09:54,000
for birds to exploit,

239
0:09:54.26,000 --> 0:09:56,000
language opened up the sphere of cooperation

240
0:09:56.26,000 --> 0:09:58,000
for humans to exploit.

241
0:09:58.26,000 --> 0:10:,000
And we take this utterly for granted,

242
0:10:00.26,000 --> 0:10:03,000
because we're a species that is so at home with language,

243
0:10:03.26,000 --> 0:10:05,000
but you have to realize

244
0:10:05.26,000 --> 0:10:08,000
that even the simplest acts of exchange that we engage in

245
0:10:08.26,000 --> 0:10:11,000
are utterly dependent upon language.

246
0:10:11.26,000 --> 0:10:13,000
And to see why, consider two scenarios

247
0:10:13.26,000 --> 0:10:15,000
from early in our evolution.

248
0:10:15.26,000 --> 0:10:17,000
Let's imagine that you are really good

249
0:10:17.26,000 --> 0:10:19,000
at making arrowheads,

250
0:10:19.26,000 --> 0:10:22,000
but you're hopeless at making the wooden shafts

251
0:10:22.26,000 --> 0:10:25,000
with the flight feathers attached.

252
0:10:25.26,000 --> 0:10:28,000
Two other people you know are very good at making the wooden shafts,

253
0:10:28.26,000 --> 0:10:31,000
but they're hopeless at making the arrowheads.

254
0:10:31.26,000 --> 0:10:33,000
So what you do is --

255
0:10:33.26,000 --> 0:10:36,000
one of those people has not really acquired language yet.

256
0:10:36.26,000 --> 0:10:38,000
And let's pretend the other one is good at language skills.

257
